Mock functions allow you to test the links between code by erasing the actual implementation of a function, capturing calls to the function (and the parameters passed in those calls), capturing instances of constructor functions when instantiated with new, and allowing test-time configuration of return values.

There are two ways to mock functions: Either by creating a mock function to use in test code, or writing a manual mock to override a module dependency.

Mock functions, also known as spies, are special types of functions in software testing that are used to track the behavior of the code being tested. They are typically used when you need to test the interactions between different components of your application and verify that they are working as expected.

A mock function acts as a substitute for the real function that it is spying on, allowing you to control its behavior and capture information about how it was used. For example, you can use a mock function to check that a particular function was called with the correct arguments, or to observe how many times a function was called. This information can then be used to validate the correct functioning of your code and make sure that it meets the desired specifications.

Mock functions are commonly used in unit testing and can be created using testing frameworks such as Jest, Mocha, or Sinon.js. They can also be created manually, but this requires a deeper understanding of how mock functions work and can be more time-consuming and error-prone.

